Fix _tkinter compilation failure on gcc 14+ (Python 2.7 + Tcl 8.6 + UCS4).

gcc 14 promoted -Wincompatible-pointer-types from warning to error by
default. Modules/_tkinter.c:1178 calls Tcl_NewUnicodeObj(inbuf, size)
where inbuf is Py_UNICODE* (a 4-byte int on --enable-unicode=ucs4
builds) and Tcl_NewUnicodeObj takes `const Tcl_UniChar*` (a 2-byte
unsigned short in Tcl 8.6). The line only runs when the two pointee
sizes match at runtime — which is FALSE on UCS4-Py + Tcl-8.6 — so it's
dead code, but gcc checks the call-site types regardless and refuses.

The explicit cast makes gcc accept the declaration. Runtime is
unaffected: the surrounding `if` is false on this configuration, so
the cast never executes. The UCS4→UTF-16 transcode fall-through path
(immediately below) is what actually runs.

--- Modules/_tkinter.c
+++ Modules/_tkinter.c
@@ -1175,7 +1175,11 @@
             return NULL;
         }
         if (sizeof(Py_UNICODE) == sizeof(Tcl_UniChar))
-            return Tcl_NewUnicodeObj(inbuf, size);
+            /* Dead branch on UCS4-Py + Tcl-8.6 (the sizes differ). The
+             * cast is required only to keep gcc 14+ happy; at runtime
+             * the if above is false and control falls through to the
+             * transcode path below. */
+            return Tcl_NewUnicodeObj((const Tcl_UniChar *)inbuf, size);
         allocsize = ((size_t)size) * sizeof(Tcl_UniChar);
         if (allocsize >= size)
             outbuf = (Tcl_UniChar*)attemptckalloc(allocsize);
